[src:visual-basic-net/programming-guide] As with any modern programming language, Visual Basic supports many common programming constructs and language elements.
[src:visual-basic-net/programming-guide] This guide describes all the major elements of programming with Visual Basic.
[src:visual-basic-net/programming-guide] Program Structure and Code Conventions Contains documentation on the basic structure and code conventions of Visual Basic, such as naming conventions, comments in code, and limitations within Visual Basic.
[src:visual-basic-net/programming-guide] Visual Basic Language Features Provides links to topics that introduce and discuss important features of Visual Basic, including LINQ and XML literals.
[src:visual-basic-net/programming-guide] COM Interop Explains the interoperability issues associated with creating and using component object model (COM) objects with Visual Basic.
[src:visual-basic-net/programming-guide] Visual Basic Language Reference Provides reference information about various aspects of Visual Basic programming.
[src:visual-basic-net/programming-guide] Visual Basic Command-Line Compiler Offers information on using the Visual Basic command-line compiler, the compiler options, and the Keyword Upgrade tool.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Microsoft's integrated development environment (IDE) for developing in Visual Basic is Visual Studio.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Most Visual Studio editions are commercial; the only exceptions are Visual Studio Express and Visual Studio Community, which are freeware.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] In addition, the .NET Framework SDK includes a freeware command-line compiler called vbc.exe.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Mono also includes a command-line VB.NET compiler.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Visual Basic is often used in conjunction with the Windows Forms GUI library to make desktop apps for Windows.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Programming for Windows Forms with Visual Basic involves dragging and dropping controls on a form using a GUI designer and writing corresponding code for each control.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] The Windows Forms library is most commonly used to create GUI interfaces in Visual Basic.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] All visual elements in the Windows Forms class library derive from the Control class.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] This provides the minimal functionality of a user interface element such as location, size, color, font, text, as well as common events like click and drag/drop.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] The Control class also has docking support to let a control rearrange its position under its parent.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Forms are typically designed in the Visual Studio IDE.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] In Visual Studio, forms are created using drag-and-drop techniques.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] A tool is used to place controls (e.g., text boxes, buttons, etc.) on the form (window).
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Controls have attributes and event handlers associated with them.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Default values are provided when the control is created, but may be changed in the Visual Studio IDE GUI or in code.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Many attribute values can be modified during run time by code such as based on user actions, or changes in the environment, providing a dynamic application.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] For example, code can be inserted into the form resize event handler to reposition a control so that it remains centered on the form, expands to fill up the form, etc.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] By inserting code into the event handler for a keypress in a text box, the program can automatically translate the case of the text being entered, or even prevent certain characters from being inserted.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Visual Basic uses statements to specify actions.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] The most common statement is an expression statement, consisting of an expression to be evaluated, on a single line.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] As part of that evaluation, functions or subroutines may be called and variables may be assigned new values.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] To modify the normal sequential execution of statements, Visual Basic provides several control-flow statements identified by reserved keywords.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Structured programming is supported by several constructs including two conditional execution constructs (`If` ...
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] `End Select` ) and four iterative execution (loop) constructs (`Do` ...
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] `To` statement has separate initialisation and testing sections, both of which must be present.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] (See examples below.) The `For Each` statement steps through each value in a list.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] It prints "*Hello, World!*" on a command-line window.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Modules are a division of code, which can contain any kind of object, like constants or variables, functions or methods, or classes, but can not be instantiated as objects like classes and cannot inherit from other modules.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Modules serve as containers of code that can be referenced from other parts of a program.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] It is common practice for a module and the code file which contains it to have the same name.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] However, this is not required, as a single code file may contain more than one module or class.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] This line defines a subroutine called "Main".
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] "Main" is the entry point, where the program begins execution.
