[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] *Console* is a system object, representing a command-line interface (also known as a "console") and granting programmatic access to the operating system's standard streams.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] The program calls the *Console* method *WriteLine,* which causes the string passed to it to be displayed on the console.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Instead of Console.WriteLine, an alternative is MsgBox, which prints the message in a dialog box instead of a command-line window.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Whether Visual Basic .NET should be considered as just another version of Visual Basic or a completely different language is a topic of debate.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] There are new additions to support new features, such as structured exception handling and short-circuited expressions.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Also, two important data-type changes occurred with the move to VB.NET: compared to Visual Basic 6, the `Integer` data type has been doubled in length from 16 bits to 32 bits, and the `Long` data type has been doubled in length from 32 bits to 64 bits.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] This is true for all versions of VB.NET.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] A 16-bit integer in all versions of VB.NET is now known as a `Short`.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Similarly, the Windows Forms editor is very similar in style and function to the Visual Basic form editor.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] The increased breadth of the latter was also a problem that VB developers had to deal with when coming to the language, although this was somewhat addressed by the *My* feature in Visual Studio 2005.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] The changes altered many underlying assumptions about the "right" thing to do with respect to the performance and maintainability of applications.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Some functions and libraries no longer exist; others are available, but not as efficient as the "native" .NET alternatives.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Even if they compiled, most converted Visual Basic 6 applications required some level of refactoring to take full advantage of the .NET language.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Microsoft provided documentation to cover changes in language syntax, debugging applications, deployment, and terminology.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] A popular trade book designed to ease the transition was Michael Halvorson's *Microsoft Visual Basic .NET Professional Step by Step*, published in 2002 by Microsoft Press.
