[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] C# and Visual Basic are Microsoft's first languages made to program on the .NET Framework (later adding F# and more; others have also added languages).
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Though C# and Visual Basic are syntactically different, that is where the differences mostly end.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Microsoft developed both of these languages to be part of the same .NET Framework development platform.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] They are both developed, managed, and supported by the same language development team at Microsoft.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] They compile to the same intermediate language (IL) known as CIL, which runs against the same .NET Framework runtime libraries.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] Both languages reference the same Base Classes of the .NET Framework to extend their functionality, and both languages can reference compiled code written in the other language.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] As a result, with few exceptions, a program written in either language can be run through a simple syntax converter to translate to the other.
[src:visual-basic-net/visual-basic-net] There are many open source and commercially available products for this task.
